<section xml:id="sec-integration-intro" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integration</title>

Geometrically, a definite integral represents the area <m>A</m> between a curve <m>f</m> and the horizontal axis over an interval <m>[a,b]</m>. 

\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[height=4in, width=4in, axis lines = middle,  xmin = -10, xmax = 10, ymin = -10, ymax = 10, xtick={3.14/4,6.28}, xticklabels={$a$,$b$},ytick=\empty,samples=\samplesize,xlabel={$x$ },ylabel={$y$ }, grid=none]
\addplot[domain=3.14/4:6.28,fill=gray!40] {x*sin(deg(x))/2+4}\closedcycle;
     \addplot[domain=-10:10,thick,black]{x*sin(deg(x))/2+4};
     \node at (3.2,2) {$A$};
      \end{axis}
    \end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

To underestimate the area <m>A</m>, we place rectangles below the curve by first creating a \textbf{partition} <m>P</m> of the interval <m>[a,b]</m> as <m>P=\{a=t_0<t_1<\cdots <t_n=b\}</m>. Each subinterval <m>[t_{i-1}, t_i]</m> on the horizontal axis serves as the base of a rectangle, and to produce a rectangle below the curve, we take <m>\inf\{f(x): x\in [t_{i-1}, t_i]\}</m> to be the rectangles height. If instead we take <m>\sup \{f(x): x\in [t_{i-1}, t_i]\}</m>, we get a rectangle above the curve over that subinterval.

